For four euros, the carriers in the Indonesian volcano area are gambling with their lives and their health as they lay 70 kilos of sulfur down on steep stone trails.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and there are those who literally work in hell.
This is the case for Anta Wijay, one of the 400 miners who make his living conquering the sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Because of this, they have to fry every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulphur gases escape from the inside of the Earth and pass into a solid state when in contact with the air.
After choping up large sulfur blocks, which together weigh up to 70 kilos, they take them to their shoulders in two bamboo baskets along steep stone trails.
To the top of the volcano, which towered 2,386 metres, it is only 250 metres, but it takes the exhausted carriers over 40 minutes to climb up the turtledist pace as they keep their balance and carefully consider their steps to avoid slipping and crash into the abyss.
They know that any stumble could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who crashed from the rows of Kawah Ijen years ago.
The miners in Kawah Ijen earn five cents for every kilo of sulfur they extract
When they're up, they make their way past the tourists who photograph them as if they were monkeys in the circus, and wearily carry the heavy baskets to the weight that the mining company has placed a little lower, at an altitude of 1850 meters.
It is PT Candi Ngrimbi, which has benefited from the volcano since 1960 and has never paid its workers more than 662 Indonesian rupees (five cents) per kilo of sulphur.
It is then sold for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, as this mineral has its place in everyday life and is used for the production of matches, fun pyrotechnics, cosmetics, dynamite and even whitening of sugar.
"Because it is normally worn 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (€3.8) for each trip," explains Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
One trip takes him three hours and is destroyed at the end, but he can earn 138,000 rupees (€11.5) per day.
While this seems to be a negligible amount for such an inhumane effort, it is three times what he would make in the field.
"The miners' daily wage is very high here. For example, collecting coffee is paid for 15,000 rupees (€1.2) per day, and the salary for a fortnight is two million rupees (€166))," explains the porter who previously worked on the tourist island of Bali as a bricklayer.
There his salary was 75,000 rupees (€6.2) per day, and the work was not so hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a serious reason, which is as convincing in Indonesia as sulphur: "I married a young girl from Bali, who is Hindu, and I took her to Jávu to convert to Islam."
Anto has asthma, it's hard to breathe, coughs all the time, and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto risks living in the Kawah Ijen volcano three times a day, the sulfur of which has already begun to take its toll on it, despite having a face protected by a special mask and glasses.
He's got asthma, he's hard to breathe, he's coughing all the time, and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases that escape from the volcano.
That's the price he has to pay to get his dream.
"I will work for two more years because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French," he promises more than a decent English.
This likeable and intelligent young man, troubled by his fate, could be a tourist guide, a waiter or a hotel receptionist, and instead does the work of a carrier.
He shares a dirty wooden shack with other porters and gets up at two o'clock every day, as the sulfur continues to rise at night and its distinctive yellow colour turns blue and glowing with darkness.
Despite the surrounding darkness, the Anto friar to the crater, illuminating his journey with a small flashlight attached to his helmet and bought it himself with his money.
About 400 carriers carry on the shoulders of a sulfur basket from the bottom of the crater
Although the company has high incomes, it has not mechanised the extraction of sulfur because of cost savings, nor does it provide any equipment for the carriers working on their own and with such effort.
In fact, they do not receive a share of the 30,000 rupees (€2.5) from the photography supplement, which, together with the ticket for 15,000 rupees (€1.2), is levied on by the natural park keepers from tourists arriving to take pictures of the volcano and its human mules.
"This job is for the cattle, and not for the people," says Madrusin, a burly 42-year-old carrier who has worked in Kawah Ijen for three decades, since he left the schools.
He manages to lift up to 110 kilos and assures us that he will keep working "as long as possible" because he needs the money to educate his three sons between the ages of 18 and 10.
I'm not retiring, I'm going to die here because the volcano was my whole life
Although sulfur burns its throat and stings in its eyes, when the wind unexpectedly turns and traps the miners in the dense fumes that emanate from the volcano, the miners are so claiming that none of them complain of suffering from serious illnesses... but this is evident from their frequent respiratory problems, arthritis, knee pain and wounds on the shoulders caused by the weight of the baskets.
The unainik who balances his basket on his back can only load 50 kilos at the age of 53.
Every day he and his colleagues dig out 15 tons of sulfur in the volcano, which the three trucks then take the steep route between the thicket to the warehouse in Tamansari, 18 kilometres away.
"I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life," Unainik declares, opening a wide mouth in which several teeth are missing.
Of his five sons, the eldest, thirty-year-old, also makes his living by mining the sulfur.
Time passes, but the incessant misery of one of the most difficult crafts in the world lingers from generation to generation - the crafts performed by human mules in Kawah Iljen.
Singapore is looking for babies to save the economy
Singaporeans are seduced by not having children, careers, stress, and the cost of living and education.
"The people of Singapore need to grow."
I'm married and I'm a patriot, you're my wife and you're a patriot. Let's fulfill our civic duty and we will be born a new life!
It may seem incredible that this slogan is part of a menthol-bonic beleg ad, but still - or perhaps that's why - the video in Singapore earlier this year was made en masse on YouTube.
These theorems are part of a rap that uses local innuendos type "let's beech in the oven" type as a mockery of the birth rate in Singapore.
The advertising agency BBH, which created the video, hopes to highlight the problem in a funny way with this ad.
The agency's artistic director, Douglas Hamilton, says he wanted to use the influence of music to make people "have a civic duty."
"This is strictly an Internet issue, so it must have been fun and funny.
It is the biggest problem in this country.
We're the worst in the world in reproduction of our population, so we felt like it was a topic that we needed to touch.
We knew the government was trying to do a lot of things like expanding pheromone perfume or organizing dating parties.
Many of these ideas might have been creative, but not entirely functional.
So we've thought about why not do the most creative possible thing, like the composition of rap, to solve the problem."
1.2 children
Whoever doesn't take it too lightly is the Singaporean government.
They spend $1,300 a year to encourage citizens to have more children.
The government's marriage and family package provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and allocates financial benefits.
But all these measures had little effect.
Singapore is a wealthy urban state with advanced technology in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its leaders and strict social controls.
The fertility rate in Singapore, with a view to stratification of the population, is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time the fertility rate exceeded the value of 2, which is considered a rate of recovery, in 1976.
Why do Singaporeans have no more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of the Marriage and Family Department of the National Office for Population says it's because of "better education" and "a wider range of career opportunities."
"People have a wider range of options at their disposal in terms of life's goals and priorities, it's not just a wedding and a family," he explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to increasing the number of free people and postponing marriage and procreating children. The result is a reduction in the birth rate in Singapore.
While immigration policy involved efforts to drastically increase the influx of immigrants as a measure against a decline in the population, this has provoked resentment among the locals.
Some of the Singapore's websites show undisguised xenophobia against many new immigrants, especially Chinese, who are criticised for maintaining low pay and a lack of effort to integrate.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why the governing Singapore party recorded its worst election result since independence last year.
After the election, there was an effort to address the problem with quotas and higher fees for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the decline in the birth rate has seen effects on national economic growth, tax revenues, health-care spending, and immigration policy, and some unexpected consequences for Singapore.
The government is trying to keep so many small houses from being built.
For example, it began to influence the real estate business.
The Office for Urban Development has begun to regulate the number of small apartments known as the "footbox" that can be built in certain urban areas.
These apartments have an area of 46 square metres and have been a great success in salesmanship.
Nevertheless, there is a fear that these apartments can support the bale's lifestyle and discourage developers from building large family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of the property developer EL Developers, claims that their "shois box" sells far faster than larger homes.
"They're more popular, by selling through days to weeks faster than larger-scale houses.
That's why they're much better for our cash flow."
Nevertheless, it admits that the new standards set clearer rules for developers who were previously capped when they wanted to offer too many small houses in one project.
Too stressed
Singapore is a city-state.
Although these new rules could be aimed at increasing the nation's fertility rate, a conversation with the Singaporeans working in the financial district of the city centre suggests that they will not have much effect.
"People are still stressed, houses are expensive, as are education, so many people postpone it," says the young official.
"The others have children.
But for me it is important to rely on my own money and time," says another, about 20-year-old, a young man.
Both men and women mention their careers, the stress, and the cost of subsistence and their education as the reasons that prevent them from having children.
So whatever the government is trying to force citizens to have children, it is the Singaporeans who have the last say on starting a family.
What is private offline is both private and online
Privacy.
According to a dictionary published by the Royal Spanish Academy, this is something of a personal nature or "the area of private life that everyone has the right to protect against any disturbance."
What is privacy for a person under the age of 16?
How does he apply this definition in his daily life and social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he is exposed to when he publishes on the internet matters he would certainly not have told anyone in a normal communication?
Journalists from elPeriódico interviewed five boys and girls between the ages of 10 and 15 who are frequent internet users.
In four cases, they considered the term privacy to be "something entirely inherent" on a personal level and a "user's name and password" if they were social networks.
"My biggest secret I would not release," says 10-year-old Jorge, in an effort to explain the importance of privacy in places such as Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"They're very secret secrets, my mom can know about them, but not the whole world," he claims.
"On FB I give nice photos or pictures of us playing.
I'm also talking to my friends there.
I wouldn't share a photo that wasn't mine or a photo that would make someone look at it," he says.
This boy realizes that it is wrong to publish obscene photographs, photographs of naked persons or photographs of crimes, or to write degrading or rude comments.
Jorge says he knows all 35 friends he has on FB and his nine Twitter followers.
Most are related.
Among them is the mother, who has the name and password of one of the accounts.
"I started a Twitter account to express my opinions and write interesting posts.
I don't know if anyone will answer me, I'm just putting them there," he adds.
"Social networks are fun, I can talk to relatives who are far away or communicate quickly with friends," he says.
Without hesitation, he says he would never accept a request from an unknown person.
He wouldn't even be interested if someone recommended someone unknown.
The case of 14-year-old Jose is different.
This teenager owns accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask networks, and admits to the latest network that he does not recognize 20 people from his list of friends.
"I'm not worried about it because we have something in common, like music," he says.
According to this boy, none of them pointed him out or asked for an address or phone number.
"If they urged me or required it from me, I would simply remove them from my account," he admits.
Jose signed up for Ask after reading the Twitter recommendation.
This boy is no stranger to experience with what is now called cyberbullying (cyberbullying).
"The well-known friend was blackmailed on the social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
He never learned who it was," he confirms.
The victim, according to Jose, did not check in from her account.
"She just activated her private mode."
Then he explains a series of steps to safely set the account.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would post pictures of acquaintances in awkward or embarrassing situations.
"Of course I would do that if I minded or just wanted to.
Even though I know it's cyberbullying," he claims.
Key issues
Marielos Porras, an English teacher and a graduate of Education and Teaching, believes that in order to navigate children and adolescents correctly in social networks, they must understand that the main objective of these networks is to inform.
He states that: "The internet originated as a means of seeking information, but when social networks came out, the rules of the game changed."
Marrielos Porras notes that academic Marc Prensky, a graduate of pedagogy at Yale University and author of the article Digital Reagents and digital immigrants, introduced these terms to explain the phenomenon.
"Digital natives are children and young people who were born at the time of this technology.
We are digital immigrants who have to teach them, yet we are yet to learn ourselves," he says.
He explains that it is a complex subject "because we ask them to discern what is appropriate to disseminate, publish and say, and what not, at an age when they are not yet mature."
Also, to be - as far as the surroundings are concerned - to be deliberate, at a time when what they most desire is to be popular, to have thousands of friends and not to think about the consequences," he adds.
According to this specialist, the most effective way to show children and adolescents what privacy is to ask questions that make them think.
"To tell them not to do something doesn't work," he adds.
Next, Marrielos Porras lists some of the options: There are some things you wouldn't tell a stranger, so why do you do it online?
Or: Would you like to see someone posting your picture the way you posted a friend's?
You know what other people are publishing about you?
When you tag the people in the pictures of the celebrations, did you ask these people permission?
And one more: Do they all need to know what you're doing right now?
The next point is to make them realise that they have to behave in the internet environment the same way they do outside of it.
It's the same rules.
"You follow respect, morality and other principles outside the internet, and one should be the same on social networks," he claims.
Supervision
Estuardo Guardia, university professor, first-grade teacher and educational adviser, explains the need for children's parents to carefully read social networking rules.
"If they understand every tricky nature, they have a good basis to talk to their children about the consequences that setting up an online account can have.
For example, in terms of age or what is allowed to be shared or published," he says.
The Guardia is of the opinion that it is crucial to remind children of the traditional "not to talk to strangers" to children.
South America Summit Ends and The Lima Declaration Has Not Disclosed
The Sixth Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) held in Peru ended today without the release of the Lima Declaration, which was announced and was reportedly signed by the seven presidents present.
The Efe Agency has repeatedly attempted to gain access to a document signed at the sixth meeting of the heads of state or government of the Unasur, but representatives of both the Foreign Ministry and the presidential office, who initially stipulated that they would publish the document after the summit, said it would be published later on the Peruvian government's website.
They also said that the content was released by Peru's President Ollanta Humala in several short press releases.
Journalists had their access to information restricted throughout the summit.
During the meeting, a video of the presidential assembly was transmitted in the press room without sound with the message "confidential session, sound transmission to be avoided."
A small amount of information available to the journalists was provided by the press officers of some of the governments who were present, but not the Peruvian spokesperson.
The only document published during the meeting was a list of attending presidents, which prompted the resentment of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more information.
Later, the Peruvian presidential office sent out an email to the media with a "final statement" from the summit, but this is just a statement by President Humala, and not an official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the third summit of the South American and Arab countries (América del Sur-País Árabes, ASPA) and, even on this occasion, the initially promised Lima Declaration was not made public, although it was fervently required by the press.
The official ASPA website shows that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities sought to ensure broadcasting for all journalists, but to completely prevent the supply of information.
The summit ended, among other things, with a joint commitment by Chile and Peru to the adoption of a judgment of the Hague Court of Justice which is settling a dispute over the border between the two countries.
President of Peru Ollanta Humala and President of Chile Sebastián Piñera met during a regional meeting and confirmed that they would respect the decision of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which would begin hearing the dispute launched by Lima against Santiago on Monday by hearing the defence of the two parties' advocacy.
"We will reload and execute a judgment that will resolve the dispute we are hearing in this international court today," President Humala said with his Chilean counterpart.
"The chil was, is and will be a country respecting international law, a peaceful resolution of disputes, conventions and international courts," Pirñera said, greeting President Humal with a handshake at the flags of both countries.
The confirmation by the two presidents that he would submit to the International Court of Justice's ruling was made public after Colombia adopted the Bogota Pact this week, in submitting to the judgments of the International Court ruling on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, and Colombia considered the decision to be wholly flawed.
The summit was held without the participation of the presidents of Brazil (Dilma Rouseff), Venezuela (Hugo Chávez), Bolivia (Evo Morales) and Argentina (Cristina Kirchner).
Paraguay was expelled from Unasur in 2011 following the dismissal of then-President Fernando Lugo and did not attend the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala was tasked with opening the morning speeches and closing the summit in Lima shortly after noon.
The president read out the final document, informing that 16 agreements had been adopted and action had been planned for 31 projects between South American countries, with investments of $17 billion.
In addition to the agreements adopted, he mentioned that UNASUR member countries would take "important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship that is for the extension of residence agreements."
He reported that actions were supported to improve "cooperation in the fight against civil uncertainty and international organised crime, to improve the availability of medicines and the cheap internet in all corners of South America, and to joint and effective measures against the risks of natural disasters."
When Europe is in crisis, "the economic consolidation (Latin America) has no winning essence, but is to be used to expand our productivity and show our nations a better future," Humala added.
"We have decided to prioritize a group of 31 symbolic projects that will improve transport links between different locations in South America, especially rural and border areas... to make our countries more closely connected and form new economic links," the Peruvian president said in a reading speech.
He mentioned that five of these projects involved Peru and the translatories of its territory from the coast to the coast to Brazil, and the other two concerned a better link with Ecuador, but did not give more details.
The final document also touched on the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve to return it to the Union of South American Nations," from which it is currently excluded.
Another of the issues highlighted by the summit was that Latin America would remain a prosperous and peaceful area that is whole and has good neighbourhood relations.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said before attending the regional meeting that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart Daniel Ortega in Mexico on Saturday to hear, with respect, the International Court of Justice's judgment on the maritime border dispute, which is questioned by Bogotá.
"It is possible that I will meet with President Daniel Ortega tomorrow (Saturday),« Santos said.
"We will discuss all the solutions, none are excluded, nor the treaty with Nicaragua that would require negotiations with this country," he stressed.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we should conduct the negotiations in the most civilised and considerate possible form possible," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico to attend the inauguration of the country's president, Enrique Peña Nita.
As part of the summit, the EU's defence ministers have met tentatively to approve the Action Plan for 2013, which seeks to strengthen the dialogue and consensus on the defence of the field.
