AIDS victims are the result of a late diagnosis today
Fabrizi was 21 years old when the result of his test was confirmed: HIV-positive.
"It was as if I had been struck by lightning," he tells me, remembering the moment of the truth, which the doctor tried to "slighten" a little, but apparently without success.
The boy kept it from his family.
He decided to take his illness on his own shoulders and began to inform himself. And with such dedication that he's already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
It is undoubtedly one of the most hitherto patients of the HIV Unit at the Civil Hospital in Guadalajara (HCG), to which he came to in 1994 after several battles with the disease.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) since the age of 22, something unimaginable in the early 1990s, when there was a lot of doubt, few treatment options and a greater stigma.
At the time, even the director of the Mexican Social Security Institute Clinic (IMSS) did not say goodbye to him "because he had a cut-off."
Back then, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Now it is possible to survive with this syndrome and live fully.
However, there are a lot of people who don't know about their disease and only come when the virus caused the body to be devastated and the immune system emitting, and then becomes victims of accidental infections.
31 years since AIDS, or at least from the first documented cases, "it has been a great success for the patient's life expectancy, which will begin treatment in a timely and appropriate manner, is exactly the same as for healthy people," said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, Head of the HIV Unit at the Civil Center in Guadalajara, noting that this information was confirmed in April this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
HIV/AIDS adden research and specialist Andrade Villanueva explained that scientists have come to the conclusion that since 2008 AIDS is not a death sentence, but that the length of survival and full life depends on the degree of disability of the immune system of patients diagnosed with the disease, better off being those who do not use drugs: people with 200 CD4 cells can live up to 30 years and people with 500 CD4 cells to 50 years.
Simply put, this means that someone who is diagnosed with HIV at the age of 25 may, according to these findings, "to live without problems until the age of 75" while adhering to the treatment," the doctor explained in an interview.
In order to highlight this progress, it is worth recalling that the average life expectancy of Mexicans is now 76.
Although the mortality rate has decreased significantly in recent years, and in the case of Mexico, the number of people who died of AIDS has fallen from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (UNSCAIDS's Joint Program) The United Nations Joint Programme for HIV/AIDS), it is also true that 60 percent of patients have died since AIDS was discovered, according to national statistics.
255 people died in the state of Jalisco alone in 2011 and so far by this May 187. However, since 2005, universal access to anti-retrovic medicinal products has been ensured.
- Why do people continue to die from the disease?
- "It seems to me that the problem is not in the possibilities of access to treatment.
That's how I see it, this is how it happens in our hospital.
At least in the last 12 years, we have not exhausted the stock of pharmaceuticals. The problem is that patients come at a very advanced stage because they don't know the state of the disease, or in the late stages of the disease."
Adds a convincing figure: "Nine out of ten patients come when an associated infection already emerges. The only thing that needs to be done to be able to make more of an impact on the overall mortality rate is to diagnose the disease earlier, so we need to offer tests on a large scale to all those who ask for it."
In his proposal, he agrees specialists and officials from the StateAIDS Prevention Board in the state of Jalisco, as well as with patients like Fabrizio, who came to have tests done at the private lab just because his friend did it, and despite his low age, he had already developed AIDS and also suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancer that is one of the usual complications.
"Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they're going to die and they don't want to know anything else.
"If I'm going to die, I'd rather have a run-in three times a week," they say, but that's not my case.
Change was for the better, I eat healthily, I exercise, I take medication."
To this day, his parents only know that he suffered from cancer.
